{
  "text": "There are also considerable data supporting a relationship between GABAergic and serotonergic systems in the CNS. Allopregnanolone has been demonstrated to directly affect the serotonin system. In rats treated with allopregnanolone for 7 days, the firing rats of serotonergic neurones in the dorsal raphe were increased. [CITATION_1] Given the hypothesis that serotonergic neurotransmission is reduced in depression, such an effect could contribute to the antidepressant-like effects of allopregnanolone. Administration of the GABA B receptor agonist, baclofen, increases serotonin release from the dorsal raphe as well as, to a lesser extent, striatum. [CITATION_2] Local infusion of the GABA A receptor antagonist, bicuculline, increases serotonin release in the dorsal raphe, indicating that GABA afferents exert a tonic inhibitory influence on serotonin neurones in the dorsal raphe. [CITATION_3] Given the serotonin hypothesis of depression, the efficacy of GABA A receptor agonists, and GABA B receptor antagonists could, at least in part, be attributed to these effects on serotonergic transmission. In terms of behavioral effects of GABAergic drugs, the profile of the GABA B antagonist, CGP56433 in the forced swim test indicates a serotoninmediated effect; CGP56433 decreases immobility and increases swimming, a profile comparable with fluoxetine. [CITATION_4] Depletion of serotonin prevents the effects of GABA B receptor antagonists in this model, further suggesting that the effect involves an interaction with serotonin. [CITATION_5] Reports in the literature also support an interaction between GABAergic and dopaminergic systems. Local application of a GABA A receptor antagonist (bicuculline) increases striatal dopamine release, whereas the GABA A receptor agonist muscimol has the opposite effect. [CITATION_6] Administration of a GABA B receptor agonist (baclofen) has no effect on striatal dopamine levels alone; however, it has been shown to attenuate nicotine-, morphine-, and cocaine-evoked dopamine release in the shell of the nucleus accumbens. [CITATION_7] In summary, GABA is strongly implicated in depression such that GABA receptors are potential targets for the development of novel antidepressants. As the GABAergic system is closely linked to monoaminergic neurotransmitter systems, manipulations of the GABAergic system are very likely to affect other neurotransmitter systems and vice versa. To what extent the effects of antidepressants on the GABAergic system contribute to the efficacy of these drugs as antidepressants remains to be determined.",
